article.headline: Arizona State 83, Oregon State 79
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- After Arizona State lost for the sixth time in seven games -- an 83-76 defeat by Oregon -- Sun Devils coach Rob Evans called for more toughness from his young team. As always, Ike Diogu responded under pressure. So did Stevie Moore and Jamal Hill. Diogu had 24 points and 15 rebounds, and Moore and Hill made clutch free throws near the end to lift Arizona State to an 83-79 win over Oregon State on Saturday night. "We executed on the offensive end, and I thought it was a sign of growth that we were in pretty good shape in the ballgame," Evans said. "They got a lead, and we kept battling and fighting back and stepped up late." Hill had 17 points, and Keith Wooden and Jason Braxton scored 12 apiece for Arizona State (8-8, 2-5 Pac-10), which won its sixth straight against the Beavers in Tempe. David Lucas had a career-high 27 points for Oregon State (8-9, 2-5). Chris Stephens scored 11 and J.S. Nash 10. The Beavers made up a nine-point deficit in the second half to lead 74-70 with 4:14 left. Diogu, a preaseason All-American, scored in double figures for the national-best 48th consecutive time, going 16-of-22 from the free-throw line to come within one of the school's record for attempts. Moore opened an 81-77 lead with his two free thows with 31.6 seconds remaining. After Nash drove for a dunk, Hill made two with 15.1 seconds to go. Moore, the team's second-leading scorer, had a 1-for-10 shooting night, but his play at the end included a partial block of Stephens' 3-point attempt. That forced an air ball that dropped into Diogu's hands as time ran out. Nash's left-handed bank shot gave the Beavers a 76-73 lead with 2:49 left, but the game turned on a foul by Lucas 24 seconds later, followed by a technical on Kyle Jeffers. Diogu made only two of the four free throws, but made both when he was fouled by Jeffers with 1:38 to go, and the Sun Devils regained the lead at 77-76. "Big momentum change," Diogu said. "I only made two out of the four free throws, but it was a big momentum change." Oregon State coach Jay John was proud of his team's defense and competitive play. "David has to learn to hold himself together in that situation," John said. "And this game was a series of situations that, next time they're placed in them, hopefull we'll be able to keep our cool." The Sun Devils were leading 62-55 when Wooden missed the front end of a one-and-one with 9:15 to go. Oregon State responded with a 13-2 run to take a 68-64 lead with 6:32 to play. Lucas and Jeffers had a basket and two free throws each during the spurt, and Stephens tied the game for the first time at 62 with a 3-pointer at the 8:31 mark. "I was getting the ball and we were scoring," Lucas said. "We were in rhythm. We were playing together as a team, and it felt good at the time." Lucas had a personal 6-0 run in the first 1:44 of the second half, and Oregon State closed within 43-40. The Sun Devils surged again, taking a 56-47 lead with 14:08 left on Allen Morill's dunk after Jeffers fell and lost a defensive rebound. The Sun Devils had two early 10-point leads, both after layups by Braxton. But the Beavers outscored Arizona State 17-11 in a 6:14 span capped by Nash's 3-pointer that lifted the Beavers within 27-23 with 8:00 remaining in the first half.
